# JWT Authentication — Performatics Timesheet System

## Overview

This system uses JSON Web Tokens (JWT) to authenticate users. On login, the server issues two tokens:

- **Access Token** — short-lived (8h), sent with every API request
- **Refresh Token** — long-lived (7d), used only to renew an expired access token

---

## User Roles

Every account has one of three roles, which controls what they can do:

| Role    | View | Create | Update | Delete | Register Accounts |
| ------- | :--: | :----: | :----: | :----: | :---------------: |
| Staff   |  ✅  |   ❌   |   ❌   |   ❌   |        ❌         |
| Manager |  ✅  |   ✅   |   ✅   |   ❌   |        ❌         |
| Admin   |  ✅  |   ✅   |   ✅   |   ✅   |        ✅         |

---

## Auth Endpoints

| Endpoint             | Method | Auth Required | Description                           |
| -------------------- | ------ | ------------- | ------------------------------------- |
| `/api/auth/login`    | POST   | None          | Log in and receive tokens             |
| `/api/auth/register` | POST   | Admin token   | Create a new staff account            |
| `/api/auth/refresh`  | POST   | None          | Get a new access token                |
| `/api/auth/me`       | GET    | Bearer token  | Get current user's account details    |
| `/api/auth/logout`   | POST   | Bearer token  | Confirm logout (client clears tokens) |

---

## How to Use

### 1. Login

```http
POST /api/auth/login
{ "username": "john_doe", "password": "Secure@123" }
```

Returns `accessToken`, `refreshToken`, and account details.

### 2. Make Authenticated Requests

Include the access token in the `Authorization` header:

```
Authorization: Bearer <accessToken>
```

### 3. Refresh an Expired Token

```http
POST /api/auth/refresh
{ "refreshToken": "<refreshToken>" }
```

### 4. Logout

Delete both tokens from localStorage and cookies on the client side.

